QA-focused test management UI layout

Current baseline (from repo)





Stack: React 19 + Vite + TypeScript in [apps/web](apps/web); urql to /graphql; routing in [apps/web/src/App.tsx](apps/web/src/App.tsx).



Styling today: Plain CSS ([apps/web/src/index.css](apps/web/src/index.css), [apps/web/src/layout/AppShell.tsx](apps/web/src/layout/AppShell.tsx) + AppShell.css / App.css)—no Tamagui/Mantine/MUI yet ([apps/web/package.json](apps/web/package.json)).



Product constraints: Local-first MVP, URL-driven project scope, no auth UI—see [.notes/FE_MVP_SPEC.md](.notes/FE_MVP_SPEC.md).



UI automation today: Playwright only (apps/web/e2e/*.spec.ts), Chromium desktop, data-testid hooks (e.g. [apps/web/e2e/fe-b-projects.spec.ts](apps/web/e2e/fe-b-projects.spec.ts)); servers started via [apps/web/playwright.config.ts](apps/web/playwright.config.ts). Spec already mentions Vitest + Testing Library as optional—not wired in tcms-web yet.

Why Tamagui (aligned with native mobile later)

Decision: Adopt Tamagui for the web app now so the presentation layer is one design system that can later target React Native / Expo with the same token/theme model and largely the same primitive components (Stack, Text, Button, Input, sheets, dialogs where supported).

Compared to a web-only library (e.g. Mantine):





Pros: Strong path to reuse UI building blocks on native; compile-time optimizations (with the Vite/Babel plugin configured); consistent spacing/typography via tamagui.config.



Tradeoffs vs Mantine-style admin kits: Less “batteries-included” for complex data tables (sorting, column resize, virtualization)—plan to compose ScrollView + header row + row components or adopt a headless table pattern + Tamagui-styled cells; verify React 19 + Vite 8 peer compatibility during implementation and pin versions per Tamagui’s current docs.



Shared future work: Extract GraphQL operations / hooks into a shared package when the mobile app starts; tokens in tamagui.config are the single source of truth for web + Expo.

